LGPL-licensed native libraries (optional features, off by default)
--------------------------------------------------------------------

The `genicam` and `rtsp` Cargo features are NOT enabled by default (this
crate's default features are `standalone` + `onvif` only). When a build
explicitly enables them, this crate dynamically links, at build/run time
via pkg-config, the following LGPL-licensed system libraries. Their
source is not vendored or statically linked into this repository or its
build output:

- Aravis (GenICam camera library) — LGPL-2.1-or-later
  https://github.com/AravisProject/aravis
  Enabled by: `genicam` feature, via the in-repo `aravis-scoped` FFI crate
  (itself Apache-2.0), which binds to the system-installed library.

- GLib — LGPL-2.1-or-later
  https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/glib
  Pulled in transitively by Aravis (`genicam`) and GStreamer (`rtsp`).

- GStreamer (core) — LGPL-2.1-or-later
  https://gitlab.freedesktop.org/gstreamer/gstreamer
  Enabled by: `rtsp` feature, via the `gstreamer`/`gstreamer-app` Rust
  binding crates (themselves MIT/Apache-2.0), which bind to the
  system-installed libraries.

Dynamic linking against an LGPL library is the standard pattern that does
not itself place the linking application under LGPL terms; it does
require that the LGPL component remain separately replaceable/relinkable
by the end user. Any build or deployment image using the `genicam` or
`rtsp` features must continue to link Aravis/GLib/GStreamer dynamically —
never statically bundle their source into this project's own binary.

GStreamer plugin caveat
------------------------

GStreamer discovers plugins dynamically at runtime; which plugins are
present is a property of the deployment host or container image, not of
this crate's Cargo dependencies. Some commonly-used GStreamer plugins
(e.g. in gst-plugins-ugly/gst-plugins-bad, and certain codec wrappers) are
licensed under the GPL, not the LGPL — loading a GPL-licensed plugin into
the same process carries a materially stronger copyleft obligation than
the LGPL core alone. Any container image or deployment target that
enables the `rtsp` feature must have its installed GStreamer plugin set
audited for GPL-licensed plugins before being distributed under LICENSE.

This is a factual/technical disclosure, not legal advice on LGPL linking
obligations or GPL plugin exposure — have counsel review before enabling
`genicam`/`rtsp` in any distributed build.
